# Git Workflow

## Work on a branch

Before starting any feature or task, ensure you are on a dedicated branch (not `main`/`master`).

```bash
git checkout -b my-feature
```

## Commit every edit

Each individual code change must be committed immediately after it is made. Do not batch unrelated edits into a single commit.

- One logical change = one commit
- Use a clear, imperative commit message describing why this change was made
  - Typically, the "what" of a commit is far less important - when commits are small, it often adds nothing of value to a commit.
  - The "what" of a commit usually will not fit in a concise, 50 char message - if it is truly required, include it in the commit message "details" (after two new lines)
- Commit before moving on to the next change

```bash
git add <changed files>
git commit -m "Add FOV reset on cutscene start"
```

## Why this matters

A granular commit history acts as a living changelog. It lets reviewers follow the reasoning behind each decision, makes bisecting bugs straightforward, and ensures no work is lost if a session is interrupted.
